**Why unmixed counts are bad for GMM-on-log.** The per-cell unmixed
GFP count is integer-valued and dominated by a delta-spike at 0/1 spots
(frac_zero = 0.44–0.70). On log axis this is a discrete spike near
ln 1 = 0 plus a sparse heavy tail to ln ≈ 7. BIC happily picks K=6 to fit
the spikes; the rightmost-pair intersection still produces a cutoff but
the GMM bimodality assumption is violated.

**Why unmixed density still loses.** Joining counts with HCR cell
volume restores a smooth bimodal log-distribution
(`fig figures/{sid}_unmixed_density.png` left panels), but on the gate
the depth profile of unmixed GFP+ is *more* concentrated in deep cortex
than the baseline. The CZ inhibitory profile peaks mid-cortex
(~200–500 µm); unmixed GFP+ peaks ~300–500 µm (782149) or rises
monotonically toward 800–1000 µm (788406). Pairwise unmixing
preferentially removes spots near other cells, so it demotes more
cells in **dense** mid-cortical layers and fewer in **sparse** deep
layers, increasing depth bias rather than reducing it.

**Verdict.** Pairwise unmixing in its current form **does not improve**
the BIC-GMM GFP+ threshold's depth-density CV. None of the 4 subjects
pass the 0.20 bar with unmixed features. On the two subjects with a
direct comparison, CV worsens by ~+0.14–0.21 absolute (~+45 % to
+65 % relative). 755252/767022 have unmixed CV inside the historical
07c "0.21–0.38" range so we cannot rule unmixing in or out for them
without recovering `cell_data_mean_*_R1.csv`.

**Implications.** The 07c-era memory line "next candidate is image-level
488 NCC" still stands. Pairwise-unmixing GFP+ counts are not a drop-in
replacement for `*_spot_488_counts.csv` in 04/R1 GFP+ thresholding —
adopting them would *worsen* the depth-density profile, which already
caps M1 sz at −70.8 % systematic bias.

